title: -Neutron capture and fission cross section of americium-243 in the energy range from 5 to 250 keV.

x4freetext: -Neutron capture and fission cross section of
americium-243 in the energy range from
5 to 250 keV.
3 MV Van de Graaff providing a pulsed
proton beam with energy just above threshold
for the neutron producing reactions.
Beam currents up to 25 micro-A  at a
repetition rate of 2.5 MHz.
.Kinematically collimated neutrons were obtained from
the following reactions -
neutron energy range  5 - 100 keV
neutron energy range 40 - 250 keV
.water cooled targets.
.Four samples were mounted in a low mass sample
changer and cycled automatically into the
measuring position.
1) A sintered pellet of americium dioxide with
isotopic composition 99.82% Am243,
weight 0.970 g, thickness .0014 atoms/barn.
2) A 99.9% pure gold sample.
Weight 2.936 g,thickness 0.005832 atoms/barn
3) natural graphite.
Weight 0.256 g thickness 0.008339 atoms/barn
( thickness adjusted to give approximately
the same scattering yield as the gold sample)
4) U235 metal with isotopic composition
weight 1.624 g thickness 0.00252 atoms U235/barn
.the samples were all canned in the same way to
obtain a similar time dependent background.
Time of flight with path lengths in the range
5 to 10 cm.
.A variety of individual runs was performed with
modified experimental parameters to check for
systematic uncertainties.
Run   detector    flight    evaluated    measuring
shielding   path      neutron      time
thickness   (cm)      En range     (hours)
(cm)                  (keV)
Two Moxon-Rae detectors with graphite and
bismuth-graphite converters.
NE-213 liquid scintillator operating with a
pulse shape discriminator to distinguish
capture events from fission events.
.These two detectors were located at a backward angle
of 120 degrees to the beam axis and were completely
outside the cone of the neutron source. They were
shielded with lead against gamma radiation from the
neutron-producing target.
Two Li-6 glass detectors located at flight
path distances of 50 and 120 cm and at angles
of 0 and 20 degrees to the proton beam were
used as neutron flux monitors.
Capture and fission gammas
fission neutrons
.Flight path differences-
-between sample and reference sample
( less than 0.7 milli-m )
-between the two neutron producing targets
( less than 0.1 milli-m )
.Neutron flux differences for sample and reference
sample due to gradual decrease in neutron
production rate with time. ( Normalization
factors always less than 1.3% )
.Time dependent and time independent background.
.Fission gammas detected in Moxon-Rae detector
( average value 1.2% ).
calculated from ratio of fission neutrons ( observed
with NE-213 scintillator ) to fission gammas
( observed with Moxon-Rae detector and U235 sample )
taking into account-
-gammas produced by U235 and impurity U238 capture
-differences between U235 and Am243 fission param.
( nubar,fission neutron energy spectra and
total fission gamma energy )
.No correction was needed for impurity Am241 neutron
capture.
.Multiple scattering and self shielding correction
calculated using the Monte-Carlo code `SESH`.(about 2%
except for Au197 where values up to 6% were obtained)
.Gamma-ray self absorption, calculated from the total
energy absorption cross section and checked for Au
against measurements of capture yields from samples
of different thicknesses.
.No correction for the influence of the lead
shielding in front of the Moxon-Rae detectors.
The measured capture yield from a U238 sample was
found to be independent (within experimental accuracy)
of the lead thickness. Similar results were found for
the capture gamma spectra of U238 and Am241 and this
was assumed to hold for Am243 also.
.Differences in detector dead time for sample and
reference sample due to the high background from
Am243 radioactivity. ( 0.03%, 0.28%,
0.8% and 2.16% for runs I to IV
respectively. No correction for runs V to VIII
where a thicker lead shielding was used )
.detector efficiency differences for sample and
reference sample due to differences in capture
gamma spectra. Correction factors calculated for
U238 and Am241 from the statistical model capture
gamma spectra and the curve of detector efficiency
against gamma energy ( evaluated from literature )
the Am241 factors were used for Am243 since-
-Am241 and Am243 have very similar nuclear structure
-correction factors depend weakly on energy spectrum.
Statistical error
systematic error
total error
.the systematic error contains the following contrib.
1) capture cross section data
-sample mass
-flight path
-time dependent and time independent background
-discriminating between capture and fission events
-multiple scattering and self shielding
-neutron flux variation
-gamma-ray self absorption
-lead shielding in front of Moxon-Rae detectors
-dead time correction
-detector efficiency
2) fission cross section data
-sample mass
-flight path
-time dependent and time independent background
-unfolding procedure used for fission neutron time
distribution
-isotopic impurities
-background due to incomplete gamma discrimination
-fraction of fission neutrons above threshold
-average number of fission neutrons
-multiple scattering
-neutron flux variations
-angular distribution of fission neutrons
A.P.T.
HH main ref added
